          "body": "1 Kings 18 functions as a *rib* — a formal covenant lawsuit. Yahweh's covenant with Israel at Sinai promised rain for obedience and drought for idolatry (Deuteronomy 11:13-17; 28:23-24). For three-and-a-half years the heavens have been brass over Israel's Baal-altars — the very god they trusted for rain has been mute while the covenant-God they spurned has shut the sky. Now the prophet returns, summons all Israel to Carmel, and stages a public adjudication. The structure is forensic: accusation (you have forsaken the commandments, 18:18); evidence (Baal's silence over twelve hours; Yahweh's fire in moments); verdict (the LORD, He is God, 18:39); covenant enforcement (the false prophets executed at Kishon, per Deuteronomy 13); covenant restoration (the rain returns, 18:41-45). Reading the chapter as anything less than covenant prosecution flattens its theology into a magic-contest."
